We don&#39;t have an actual script to test for the vulnerability, but the procedure to test for it is pretty straightforward. Details are in the original announcement at&#58;
<a href='11248' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//ticket.grid.iu.edu/goc/viewer?id=11248</a>

the specific instructions for testing for the vulnerability are copied below&#58;

Details
=======

To test for the vulnerability, prepare a specially-formatted tarfile
called gratia_foo.tar.gz on a local machine. The tar file should contain
a directory, which contains an example file to be checked for.

On the target machine (adjust PROBENAME, ce.example.com,
collector.example.com, and PORT accordingly), as a local user&#58;
mkdir -p
/tmp/gratiafiles/subdir.PROBENAME_ce.example.com_collector.example.com_PORT/staged/store
cp gratia_foo.tar.gz
/tmp/gratiafiles/subdir.PROBENAME_ce.example.com_collector.example.com_PORT/staged/store/tz.gratia_foo.tar.gz

For the next run of Gratia, the probe (running as root) will uncompress
the tarfile.  Because the tarfile contains a
directory, Gratia will be unable to delete it, and the file
will remain in /tmp after the probe finishes running.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='12573#1350420316'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2012-10-16T20:45:16+00:00">Oct 16, 2012 08:45 PM UTC</time> by <b>echism</b><a class="anchor" name="1350420316">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Security Team,

